ght be.\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"title\": \"Observing Convergence from Both Sides\",\n            \"timestamp\": \"00:04:12\",\n            \"summary\": \"This subsection continues the numerical exploration by calculating average speeds over intervals approaching t=1 from values less than 1. Intervals such as [0, 1], [0.5, 1], and [0.999, 1] are used to show that the average speed also approaches the same value as when approaching from the right. The consistent convergence from both sides reinforces the idea that the function's behavior is settling towards a particular number. This dual-sided approach is crucial for a complete understanding of limits.\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"title\": \"Introducing Limit Notation\",\n            \"timestamp\": \"00:05:08\",\n            \"summary\": \"This segment formally introduces the standard mathematical notation for a limit: `lim (as x->a) f(x) = L`. It explains that 'L' represents the value that f(x) approaches as 'x' gets arbitrarily close to 'a'. The key takeaway is that 'x' approaches 'a' but never actually equals 'a'. The notation concisely captures the concept of the value a function tends toward.\"\n          }\n        ]\n      },\n      {\n        \"title\": \"Evaluating Limits and Cases Where They Don't Exist\",\n        \"subsections\": [\n          {\n            \"title\": \"Basic Limit Evaluation Examples\",\n            \"timestamp\": \"00:06:55\",\n            \"summary\": \"This subsection presents straightforward examples to illustrate how limits work for simple functions. It demonstrates that for a constant function like f(x)=5, the limit as x approaches any number is always 5. For the identity function f(x)=x, the limit as x approaches 'a' is 'a'. Similarly, for f(x)=x^2, the limit as x approaches 3 is 9, suggesting direct substitution often works for continuous functions.\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"title\": \"Limits with Discontinuities (Holes)\",\n   